sentence: After a hesitant start, stocks were trading higher Tuesday as Wall Street looks ahead to the Federal Reserve Open Market Committee tomorrow providing more definitive answers to the direction of monetary policy.
Equities also were underpinned by technical supports at 17,700 for the Dow Jones Industrial Average and 2,070 for the S&P 500, both of which remained intact despite heavy selling pressure yesterday.
In economic news, new housing starts declined 11.1% during May to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 1.036 million, missing expectations for 1.090 million new homes.
April housing starts were revised higher to a 1.165-million annualized pace from the 1.135 million first reported last month.
Permits for new construction increased by 12% to an annualized 1.275 million, topping expectations looking for a 1.105 million annual pace for new permits.
April was revised slightly lower to 1.140 million from 1.143 million.

European markets also erased earlier losses stemming from dour headlines out of Greece, including a confrontational news conference by Greek Prime Minisiter Alexis Tsipras blaming creditors for the country's insolvency.
The major EU-zone indices mostly finished on the plus side, although the U.K;s FTSE 100 closed little changed while the Athens stock exchange shed almost 5% in value.
Crude oil was up 60 cents to $60.12 per barrel.
Natural gas was down 3 cents to $2.89 per 1 million BTU.
Gold was down $6.50 to $1,179.30 per ounce, while silver was down 14 cents to $15.94 per ounce.
Copper was down 3 cents to $2.62 per pound.
Among energy ETFs, the United States Oil Fund was up 0.75% to $20.31 with the United States Natural Gas Fund was down 1.68% to $13.80.
Amongst precious-metal funds, the Market Vectors Gold Miners ETF was unchanged at 22.18 while SPDR Gold Shares were down 0.51% to $113.51.
The iShares Silver Trust was down 0.71% to $15.29.
